[4] Nepal (Kathmandu)
Date: Thu 21 Dec 2017
From: Sher Bahadur Pun, <drsherbdr@yahoo.com> [edited]


On [21 Dec 2017], 2 patients [aged 25- (patient-1) and 26- (patient-2), years old], residents of Thamel, Kathmandu, presented to the outpatient department of Sukraraj Topical and Infectious Disease Hospital with a 6-day history of severe headache, fever, and sore throat. They both developed maculopapular rashes 3 days after the initial symptoms starting on the head then neck followed by trunk and upper extremities. They (these patients) were neighbors.

According to the patient-1, his nephew (13-year old) was first infected with measles, who brought this infection from his school. Several other students were also infected with measles, resulting in absence of more students from school over the last couple of days. In another words, there was a measles outbreak in that school. A total of 3 other members from the same family (patient-1) have also been infected with measles.

It is becoming more apparent that measles in adults is increasingly seen over the past few years in Nepal. However the reason for this increased incidence rates is not yet known.

--
Sher Bahadur Pun, MD, PhD
Clinical Research Unit, Sukraraj Tropical and Infectious Disease Hospital, Kathmandu, Nepal.
<drsherbdr@yahoo.com>

[ProMED thanks Dr. Sher Bahadur Pun for submitting this report.

Although this report on the changing epidemiology of measles is from Nepal, it also has been noted that in Africa, the epidemiology of measles also is changing to affect older children and young adults as well as young children, i.e., less than 5 years old [See JL Goodson et al. Changing Epidemiology of Measles in Africa J Infec Dis 2011:204 (Suppl 1) S205].

During 2002-2009, the median age of confirmed measles was 36 months. In countries with greater than or equal to 50 percent aMCV1 (average of routine measles vaccination coverage) compared with low-coverage countries, age shifted to older children and young adults. The shift to older children and adults has implications for disease burden estimates and may disproportionately lower the measles mortality burden relative to the morbidity burden, because previously described case fatality ratios are lower in older cases.

A map of Nepal can be found at https://www.mapsofworld.com/nepal/. - Mod.LK]
